     <widget class="QTextEdit" name="textEdit_12">
      <property name="geometry">
       <rect>
        <x>130</x>
        <y>40</y>
        <width>251</width>
        <height>171</height>
       </rect>
      </property>
      <property name="markdown">
       <string>ION-Sim: EMG module. The EMG signal refers to a recording methodology typical
of surgical sessions. Subcutaneous needle electrodes (a pair for each muscle to
be monitored) are used, applied near the motor point of the muscle belly. The
system allows viewing both spontaneously generated activity (free running) and
activity triggered by an event: typically, the stimulation of the muscle's
motor nerve (cranial or peripheral) by the surgeon.

</string>
      </property>
     </widget>
    </widget>
    <widget class="QWidget" name="tab_CAP">
     <attribute name="title">
      <string>CAP</string>
     </attribute>
     <widget class="QTextEdit" name="textEdit_3">
      <property name="geometry">
       <rect>
        <x>133</x>
        <y>40</y>
        <width>251</width>
        <height>171</height>
       </rect>
      </property>
      <property name="markdown">
       <string>ION-Sim: CAP module. The compound action potential (CAP) of the peripheral
nerve (myelinated fibers), is generated by saltatory conduction, through the
nodes of Ranvier. A set of single-fiber action potentials (SFAPs) is produced,
the number and shape of which correlate to the number and type of fibers
composing the nerve at the stimulation point. The set of single-fiber
potentials (SFAPs) starts at the &quot;start,&quot; i.e., the stimulation point, and they
all travel together towards the arrival point, equivalent to the recording
electrode site. During travel, since fibers have different diameters and
conduction velocities have a linear dependence on fiber diameter, they will
arrive at different and increasingly later times, depending on the conduction
velocity of the individual fibers. Therefore, the greater the conduction
distance, the greater the dispersion of the SFAPs upon arrival, due to the
presence of a spectrum of conduction velocities of the nerve fibers, strictly
correlated to their myelinated axonal diameters.

</string>
      </property>
     </widget>
